"Ormsby A., Hodson E., Li Y., Basinger J., Kaminskyj S.","Quantitation of endorhizal fungi in High Arctic tundra ecosystems through space and time: The value of herbarium archives",2007,"Canadian Journal of Botany","85","7",,"599","606",,,10.1139/B07-044,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-35648972147&partnerID=40&md5=38de1d322e086112bfbcaf38874ac8bf","Department of Geological Sciences, University of Saskatchewan, 114 Science Place, Saskatoon, Sask. S7N 5E2, Canada; Department of Biology, University of Saskatchewan, 112 Science Place, Saskatoon, Sask. S7N 5E2, Canada","Ormsby, A., Department of Geological Sciences, University of Saskatchewan, 114 Science Place, Saskatoon, Sask. S7N 5E2, Canada; Hodson, E., Department of Biology, University of Saskatchewan, 112 Science Place, Saskatoon, Sask. S7N 5E2, Canada; Li, Y., Department of Biology, University of Saskatchewan, 112 Science Place, Saskatoon, Sask. S7N 5E2, Canada; Basinger, J., Department of Geological Sciences, University of Saskatchewan, 114 Science Place, Saskatoon, Sask. S7N 5E2, Canada; Kaminskyj, S., Department of Biology, University of Saskatchewan, 112 Science Place, Saskatoon, Sask. S7N 5E2, Canada","Mycorrhizal fungi are widespread in temperate and tropical regions, but generally are thought to be relatively depauperate at high latitudes. The potential impact of global warming on the polar ecosystems has renewed interest in research into tundra soil microbiota. Although logistical impediments limit field access, herbarium accessions are a potential resource for surveying mycorrhizal distribution. We present: (i) a method for examining fungi in roots of herbarium specimens that provides morphological preservation comparable to formalin fixation; and (ii) a multiple quantitation method to assess diverse morphotypes. Arbuscular mycorrhizae, fine endophytes, and septate endophytes were widespread in Asteraceae roots from Axel Heiberg and Ellesmere islands, Arctic Canada, during 2004. Roots from the same species collected from this region since 1982, stored in our herbarium, consistently contained abundant endorhizal fungi. Although 2004 was one of the coolest growing seasons in the survey, mycorrhizal abundance was highest in that year. Endorhizal fungi are likely to be important for plant survival and soil-forming processes in High Arctic tundra environments, and may be sensitive to climate variation. © 2007 NRC.","Arbuscular mycorrhizal fungi; Confocal epifluorescence microscopy; Fine endophyte fungi; High arctic; Multiple quantitation method; Septate endophyte fungi","Climate change; Ecosystems; Microorganisms; Soils; Arbuscular mycorrhizal fungi; Confocal epifluorescence microscopy; Fine endophyte fungi; Multiple quantitation methods; Septate endophyte fungi; Fungi; abundance; arbuscular mycorrhiza; climate variation; endophyte; fluorescence; fungus; global warming; herbarium; microscopy; survival; tundra; Arctic; Axel Heiberg Island; Canada; Ellesmere Island; North America; Nunavut; Arbuscular; Asteraceae; Fungi",,,,,,"Allen, N., Nordlander, M., McGonigle, T., Basinger, J., Kaminskyj, S., Arbuscular mycorrhizas on Axel Heiberg Island (80 °N) and at Saskatoon (52 °N) Canada (2006) Can. J. Bot, 84, pp. 1094-1100. , doi:10.1139/B06-085; Brundrett, M., Bougher, N., Dell, B., Grove, T., Malajczuk, N., Working with mycorrhizas in forestry and agriculture (1996) Monograph, 32. , Australian Centre for International Agricultural Research ACIAR, Canberra, Australia; Cunningham, J.L., A miracle mounting fluid for permanent whole-mounts of microfungi (1972) Mycologia, 64, pp. 906-911. , doi:10.2307/3757946; Dalpé, Y., Aiken, S.G., Arbuscular mycorrhizal fungi associated with Festuca species in the Canadian High Arctic (1998) Can. J. Bot, 76, pp. 1930-1938. , doi:10.1139/cjb-76-11-1930; Gianinazzi-Pearson, V., Morandi, D., Dexheimer, J., Gianinazzi, S., Ultrastructural and ultracytochemical features of a Glomus tenuis mycorrhiza (1981) New Phytol, 88, pp. 633-639; Jumpponen, A., Dark septate endophytes - are they mycorrhizal? (2001) Mycorrhiza, 11, pp. 207-211. , doi:10.1007/s005720100112; Ma, W.K., Siciliano, S.D., Germida, J.J., A PCR-DGGE method for detecting arbuscular mycorrhizal fungi in cultivated soils (2005) Soil Biol. Biochem, 37, pp. 1589-1597. , doi:10.1016/j.soilbio.2005.01.020; Malloch, D.W., Pirozynski, K.A., Raven, P.H., Ecological and evolutionary significance of mycorrhizal symbioses in vascular plants (2000) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A, 77, pp. 2113-2118. , doi:10.1073/pnas.77.4.2113; McGonigle, T.P., Miller, M.H., Evans, D.G., Fairchild, G.L., Swan, J.A., A new method which gives an objective measure of colonization of roots by vesicular-arbuscular mycorrhizal fungi (1990) New Phytol, 115, pp. 495-501. , doi:10.1111/j.1469-8137.1990.tb00476.x; Merryweather, J.W., Fitter, A.H., A modified method for elucidating the structure of the fungal partner in a vesicular-arbuscular mycorrhiza (1991) Mycol. Res, 95, pp. 1435-1437; Peterson, R.L., Massicote, H., Melville, L.H., (2004) Mycorrhizas: Anatomy and cell biology, , CABI, Wallingford, UK; Olsson, P.A., Eriksen, B., Dahlberg, A., Colonization by arbuscular mycorrhizal and fine endophytic fungi in herbaceous vegetation in the Canadian High Arctic (2004) Can. J. Bot, 82, pp. 1547-1556. , doi:10.1139/b04-111; Smith, S.E., Read, D.J., (1997) Mycorrhizal symbioses, , Academic Press, London, UK; Verheilig, H., Schweiger, P., Brundrett, M., An overview of methods for the detection and observation of arbuscular mycorrhizal fungi in roots (2005) Physiol. Plant, 125, pp. 393-404","Kaminskyj, S.; Department of Biology, University of Saskatchewan, 112 Science Place, Saskatoon, Sask. S7N 5E2, Canada; email: Susan.Kaminskyj@usask.ca",,,,,,,,00084026,,CJBOA,,"English","Can. J. Bot.",Article,Scopus,2-s2.0-35648972147
